## How It Works Now
Your Electron app starts, and main.js initializes and connects the Claude SDK.

The AI, working through the SDK, decides to perform an action. For example, it might decide to "click on the element at (x: 500, y: 250) and type 'const x = 10;'".

The SDK emits an action event inside your main.js process with a payload like:

JSON

{
  "x": 500,
  "y": 250,
  "action": "type",
  "text": "const x = 10;"
}
Your claude.on('action', ...) listener catches this and sends it to the renderer.

Your unchanged renderer/app.js code receives the command and performs the beautiful, highlighted cursor animation and simulated typing in the <webview>.

This approach is more integrated, secure, and robust, providing the exact native control you're looking for.

