The error Error: ERR_ABORTED (-3) loading 'about:blank' is the key clue. This error happens when a navigation or resource load inside a <webview> is suddenly cancelled. The most common cause is the parent window being reloaded while the webview is trying to initialize.

## Root Cause
The issue is in your main.js file, within the createMainWindow function. You have these two lines:

JavaScript

// main.js - inside createMainWindow()
this.mainWindow.webContents.session.clearCache();
this.mainWindow.webContents.reloadIgnoringCache(); // <-- This is the problem
While clearCache() is fine, the reloadIgnoringCache() call forces an immediate, hard refresh of your entire renderer window right after it loads. Your renderer code (app.js) is likely trying to set up the <webview> at the same time, and this reload aborts its initial navigation, causing the ERR_ABORTED crash.

## The Fix: Remove the Aggressive Reload
The fix is straightforward: we just need to remove that aggressive reload. The clearCache() call is usually enough to prevent caching issues during development.

Open main.js.

Find the createMainWindow method.

Comment out or delete the reloadIgnoringCache() line.

Hereâ€™s how the corrected section of main.js should look:

JavaScript

// main.js

    async createMainWindow() {
        this.mainWindow = new BrowserWindow({
            // ... webPreferences ...
        });

        await this.mainWindow.loadFile('renderer/index.html');

        // Clearing cache is fine, but we'll remove the disruptive reload.
        this.mainWindow.webContents.session.clearCache();
        // this.mainWindow.webContents.reloadIgnoringCache(); // COMMENT OUT OR DELETE THIS LINE

        // Enable dev tools to debug preload issues
        this.mainWindow.webContents.openDevTools();

        // ... rest of the function ...
    }
## Best Practice: Add Webview Error Listeners
To make your app more robust, it's a great idea to listen for errors directly on the <webview> element in your renderer code. This will help you catch and log any future issues with it.

You'll need to add this code to your renderer's JavaScript file (likely renderer/app.js), wherever you manage your webview element.

JavaScript

// renderer/app.js (or your equivalent renderer script)

// Assuming you have a reference to your webview element
const devtoolsView = document.getElementById('devtools-view'); // Use your actual webview ID

if (devtoolsView) {
    // Listen for crashes in the webview's renderer process
    devtoolsView.addEventListener('crashed', (event) => {
        console.error('ðŸ”¥ Webview has crashed!', event);
        // Use the API we created in preload.js to report it
        window.electronAPI.reportWebviewError({
            source: 'WebView',
            message: 'The DevTools webview process has crashed.'
        });
    });

    // Listen for navigation failures
    devtoolsView.addEventListener('did-fail-load', (event) => {
        // We can ignore user-cancelled events, which have the code -3
        if (event.errorCode === -3) {
            console.warn('WebView navigation aborted, likely intentional.');
            return;
        }

        console.error('ðŸ”¥ Webview failed to load:', event);
        window.electronAPI.reportWebviewError({
            source: 'WebView',
            message: `Failed to load URL: ${event.validatedURL}. Error code: ${event.errorCode}`
        });
    });
}
